Excessive murder is usually an extremely poor business investment.
If I've learned anything from playing a pagan in CKII (other than that gavelkind is the worst and its fun to raid the French) it's that concubines have absolutely amazing uses. First up it is important to let people know that being a concubine is not a punishment, it is an honor! It is a bond between ruler and subjects almost as important as a proper marriage. It is a declaration of control, yes, so is an oath of fealty, and knights flock to good kings in order to swear service. In return for this service, it is assumed that the village will be protected, its complaints judge fairly, and perhaps something special may come of it.

Having many bastards can be spun into a fine ruling strategy in several different ways. You could use them as an army of loyal administrators, all trustworthy blood relatives raised in your household as diplomats, commanders, and learned men. Or you could use the shark strategy: only one of your offspring may be the next warlord, and the one who "survives" the others will be a cunning and tough enough bastard to be a worthy heir. Just remember to abdicate early so he doesn't get any funny ideas.

There have been tales of lords who took hundreds of women as consorts, but they are fools. Take two or three, lest they squabble too much, fall for one of your guards, or plot your untimely demise.
